{"key":"processedPost-16137701","value":{"id":16137701,"first":16137585,"last":16137769,"when":1335376594,"utime":"04/25/12 08:56 PM","cleanedPost":"No, you replace the gauge.&nbsp; Don't try to seal or otherwise repair it, unless it's leaking from where it's threaded into the lid.&nbsp; In that case, tighten it up by half a turn or so.<br />You're supposed to let steam vent for five to ten minutes before putting the weight on or otherwise closing a valve so pressure can build.<br />When your jars will lose moisture is excessive rattling or venting of steam once pressure is reached.&nbsp; This is why I recommend reducing the stove to a setting that will maintain around 14 psi, once pressure is reached and steam vents a few additional times.<br />Your wbs is supposed to look dry after pressure cooking.&nbsp; If there was visible water on the grains, they wouldn't colonize properly.&nbsp; It sounds like you got the moisture content right.<br />RR"}}